Subtle difference I guess but it would've been cool

Adding an Eliksni as a Guardian first would have us think "well. The Traveler may choose multiple species of a system so long as they align with its wants" and then spend time wondering if Savathun aligns with its wants more than our worry that it's betrayed us

—must in some way be good, or at least not traitors. And so we are still focused on "how could the Traveler choose Savathun, who is Probably not for the greater good" instead of "How could the Traveler choose a Hive, who has notoriously been fully evil in the past"

While still keeping us in the thought that well the Traveler will choose people who are good. Characters like Drifter and Saladin who remember the Dark Ages have been telling us that bad people wield the Light all the time but there's still this pervading idea that all Guardians—

It would've been more interesting if we'd been like well ok but the Traveler would never choose the HIVE of all beings, rather than the Traveler will never again choose anyone but us. It's a more humbling thought process that would mean that we don't have to be infallible or dead

Like beyond being a bridge between the two species that would've made Splicer way more interesting. It would've made us realize that the Traveler can pick outside of humanity without immediately diving to "Oh shit its going to abandon us just like the Fallen."
I am of the opinion. That the lead up to Witch Queen would've been better if they had made Mithrax a Guardian also

7) Rare pairs?

What a weird question. A pairing's rarity has no effect on whether or not it scratches my little peabrain

6) Multi-chapter or oneshots?

Not to be mean but I feel like if you don't have at least one of each then you have reached a point where you ought to expand your horizons a little

5) How long do your fics tend to be?

Depends on how big the concept is. My chapter fics usually span ten chapters and anywhere from >45K and my oneshots can be from 8K to 10K. Drabbles are usually ~2K

4) past tense or present?

I generally prefer writing in present tense, though I used to use past and can still do both.

3) First person or third person?

I'm strongly of the opinion that first person is for things like poetry and autobiographical type work. Narrative first person in fiction is pretty much the only way to make me instantly put a book down or close a fic.

Always. Can't write unless I have some plot mood/character arc music going. I've actually gotten writer's block from not being able to find a jam that fits.
